        "id": "art_2026-06-27_047",
        "section": "Britain",
        "category": "analysis",
        "title": "Slipping up or down the class system is surprisingly bearable",
        "title_zh": "在阶级体系中上下流动，意外地尚可忍受",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-06-27/47",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\n英国慈善机构萨顿信托基金会的研究表明，无论在阶级体系中向上攀升还是向下流动，当代英国人的生活满意度均高于固守工人阶级身份的人群；而稳固的中产阶级才是幸福感的最高点。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n1. 向上社会流动在20世纪中叶曾是普遍经历，但如今已较为罕见，主因是制造业向服务业的经济大转型已基本完成，许多人仍能找到比父辈更好的工作，但获得更差工作的人数也在增加（见原文图表）。\n2. 萨顿信托（Sutton Trust）的凯文·拉瑟姆（Kevin Latham）与埃斯米·莉莉怀特（Esme Lillywhite）基于覆盖数万个家庭的长期调查，以职业而非自我认同来衡量社会流动，因为英国人对阶层的自我描述并不可靠——中产常夸大或虚构工人阶级出身。\n3. 稳固的中产阶级——出生于专业家庭、本人也从事专业工作的人群——在控制族裔与年龄等变量后，享有最高的生活满意度（见原文图表）。\n4. 紧随其后的是向上流动者，正如1957年约翰·布雷恩（John Braine）小说《向上爬》（Room at the Top）中工人阶级主角乔·兰普顿（Joe Lampton）所经历的那样；物质成就（更稳定工作、更高住房自有率）足以缓解身份转换带来的心理不适。\n5. 向下流动者虽不及向上流动者满意，却仍胜过工人阶级子女继续当工人；他们对闲暇时间感到满意，但抱怨薪酬，文章未记录其父母辈的感受。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n文章呈现两方观点。一方以社会学家黛安娜·里伊（Diane Reay，矿工之女）为代表的知识分子强调向上流动伴随『背叛感与强烈内疚』；另一方以本·琼斯（Ben Jones，大曼彻斯特教育政策从业者）为代表，指出向上流动者更多感受到的是现实物质差距（如缺乏专业家庭那样的安全网）而非心理背叛，文章暗示写作此类感受的知识分子群体可能本身具有特殊性。伦敦大学学院（UCL）的陈卓荣（Tak Wing Chan）等其他研究者也得出了相同模式。\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n随着制造业向服务业转型红利消退，向上流动通道收窄、向下流动风险上升的格局或将延续；物质条件（住房自有率、就业稳定性）将继续主导人们对阶层升降的主观感受，而非纯粹的身份认同焦虑。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">Britain</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | British society</span></p>\n<h1>Slipping up or down the class system is surprisingly bearable </h1>\n<h3>Much better than being solidly working-class</h3>\n<h3>June 25th 2026</h3>\n<p>“I wanted an Aston Martin, I wanted a three-guinea linen shirt, I wanted a girl with a Riviera suntan.” So Joe Lampton, the young working-class hero of “Room at the Top”, announced his desire to penetrate the professional middle class. John Braine’s novel of 1957 was one of many post-war books to feature cocky, headstrong social climbers. It ends tragically, with deception, heartbreak and death.</p>\n<p>Upward social mobility was a common experience for men and women who grew up in the mid-20th century. It is rarer these days, mostly because the great economic shift from manufacturing to services has run its course. Many people still acquire better jobs than their parents had, but a growing number find worse ones (see top chart). How do they feel about it?</p>\n<p>The Sutton Trust, a charity, recently provided some answers. Kevin Latham and Esme Lillywhite draw on a long-running survey that covers tens of thousands of families. They measure social mobility by looking at the jobs people do rather than how they describe themselves. That is wise, because Britons cannot be trusted on matters of class. Middle-class people tend to play up or invent working-class roots and overstate their own mobility.</p>\n<p>Being solidly middle-class seems to be the surest route to contentment. Once characteristics like ethnicity and age are controlled for, people who were born into professional families and do professional jobs themselves have the highest life satisfaction (see bottom chart). But another group is close behind: modern-day Joe Lamptons, who have risen higher up the occupational ladder than their parents.</p>\n<p>Other researchers, including Tak Wing Chan of University College London, have discovered the same pattern. Yet some will still find it surprising. Accounts of upward social mobility tend to emphasise dislocation and pain. Lampton felt slighted by his new middle-class associates. Others sense they have left something behind, or have somehow cheated. “It is difficult to avoid a sense of treachery and overwhelming guilt,” wrote Diane Reay, a miner’s daughter who became a prominent sociologist.</p>\n<p>Perhaps the intellectuals who write such accounts are peculiar. A working-class child who triumphs in business might feel less guilty than an educational prodigy. Besides, material success is nice—so nice that it blunts feelings of dislocation. Upwardly mobile people have better, more stable jobs than solidly working-class people, and are more likely to own their homes. Such things mostly explain their greater contentment.</p>\n<p>Material differences might also explain why social risers are a bit less contented than the established middle classes. “I’m delighted that I am where I am,” says Ben Jones, who grew up in a working-class household and now works on education policy in Greater Manchester. Meeting the children of professionals at university, he was impressed by their “certainty that things will work out”. But their ease and confidence, and his lack of it, was less a difference in attitude than an accurate reading of their different circumstances. The children of professionals tend to have strong safety nets, making them fearless. By contrast, Mr Jones soon had to care for his mother.</p>\n<p>What of the unlucky folk who end up doing more menial jobs than their parents? They seem less satisfied than the upwardly mobile, but more satisfied than the working-class children of working-class parents. Some may have happily traded high salaries for reasonable hours. The social fallers seem satisfied with their leisure time, although they resent their pay. How their parents feel is not recorded. <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>For more expert analysis of the biggest stories in Britain, <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/newsletters/blighty\">sign up</a> to Blighty, our weekly subscriber-only newsletter.</p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//britain/2026/06/25/slipping-up-or-down-the-class-system-is-surprisingly-bearable\">https://www.economist.com//britain/2026/06/25/slipping-up-or-down-the-class-system-is-surprisingly-bearable</a> </p>"
