        "title": "Strange new EV-makers keep appearing in China",
        "title_zh": "奇奇怪怪的新能源车企在中国不断涌现",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-06-27/51",
        "summary_md": "## 🌍 Business · 忠实中文翻译\n\n> 下方为英文原文的中文翻译 (按英文语义直译, 不做解读)。\n\n---\n\nBusiness | 一门吸金生意\\n\\n奇奇怪怪的新能源车企在中国不断涌现\\n\\n能造扫地机器人，就能造车\\n\\n2026年6月25日\\n\\n明年，以扫地机器人闻名的中国企业追觅（Dreame）计划开始销售造型流畅的电动汽车（EV）。从小型家电跨界到能装下一整家人的出行工具，追觅并非孤例。Rox Motor于2023年开始销售电动SUV，其创始人同样出身吸尘器大佬。小米靠廉价智能手机起家（同时也生产吸尘器等），一年后也开卖起了跑车。\\n\\n更令人意外的是，拥挤的中国电动车市场竟然仍有新玩家入场。去年至少有143个电动车品牌卖出了至少一辆车。但据咨询公司AlixPartners统计，其中46个品牌销量不足1000辆。即便如此，市场上仍新增了23个电动车品牌，仅有9个退出。\\n\\n诚然，其中许多是\"子品牌\"——大企业用来区隔高端车型与大众市场车型的产物。按销量计中国第三大车企吉利旗下品牌组合超过十个，包括极氪（Zeekr）、极星（Polestar）和领克（Lynk & Co）。\\n\\n2025年仅有十家中国企业各自售出至少100万辆车，占总销量的84%。不过这一份额较前一年略有下滑，表明业内人士长期预言的中国电动车市场整合尚未真正发生。整个公司倒闭的情况只是偶尔出现。合众汽车（旗下哪吒品牌）正在走向这一结局。去年公司突然停发许多员工工资，一度冲上头条——愤怒的员工将创始人堵在上海办公室讨薪。\\n\\n尽管如此，2026年的行业前景相当黯淡。中国汽车整体销量持续快速下滑。4月销量较去年同期下降五分之一，已连续第七个月走低。中央政府已批评电动车企自2023年起陷入恶性价格战。5月价格开始回升，暗示行业或许已开始听从政府号令。但全球最大电动车企比亚迪将此归因于芯片和电池等零部件成本上涨，这意味着利润率可能仍承压。\\n\\n随着国内需求下滑、价格上涨，中国车企将更加依赖海外销售，海外业务正以惊人的速度增长。4月海外销量同比增长80%。搭建海外分销网络既费钱又耗时。但随着行业压力持续加剧，利润率通常更高的海外销售将成为成败关键。中国电动车企正迫不及待地将它们\"吸\"入囊中。■\\n\\n如欲追踪塑造商业、工业与技术的趋势，请订阅我们的每周付费通讯《The Bottom Line》（点击阅读原文）。\\n\\n本文由zlibrary下载自https://www.economist.com//business/2026/06/24/strange-new-ev-makers-keep-appearing-in-china",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">Business</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | A sucky business</span></p>\n<h1>Strange new EV-makers keep appearing in China</h1>\n<h3>If you can make a robo-vacuum, you can make a car</h3>\n<h3>June 25th 2026</h3>\n<p>Next year Dreame, a Chinese business better known for its robo-vacuums, plans to start selling sleek electric vehicles (EVs). It is not the only firm branching out from small household appliances to machines that can carry an entire household. Rox Motor, which started selling electric SUVs in 2023, was also founded by a vacuum tycoon. Xiaomi, which made its name producing cheap smartphones (and also makes vacuums, among other things), began selling sports cars a year later.</p>\n<p>Perhaps more surprising is that there are new entrants to the crowded Chinese EV market at all. No fewer than 143 EV brands sold at least one car last year. But 46 of them did not sell more than 1,000, according to AlixPartners, an advisory firm. Even so, 23 new EV brands were launched while just nine were halted.</p>\n<p>Admittedly, lots of these are “sub-brands”, created by big companies to differentiate their high-end rides from mass-market models. Geely, China’s third-largest carmaker by sales, has a portfolio of more than ten brands, including Zeekr, Polestar and Lynk &amp; Co.</p>\n<p>Only ten Chinese companies managed to sell at least 1m cars apiece in 2025, accounting for 84% of the total. However, that share was down slightly from the year before, suggesting that the consolidation of China’s EV market that industry insiders have long predicted is yet to take place. Only occasionally does an entire company collapse. Hozon Auto, which made the Neta EV brand, is in the process of doing so. It suddenly stopped paying many of its employees last year and attracted headlines when angry staff cornered the founder at his Shanghai office demanding their wages.</p>\n<p>Still, things look rather bleak for the industry in 2026. Overall car sales in China have been falling swiftly. In April they were down by a fifth from a year earlier, marking the seventh straight month of decline. The central government has criticised EV-makers for engaging in a vicious price war since 2023. Prices started rising in May, suggesting that the industry may have started listening to the state. But BYD, the world’s largest EV-maker, attributes this instead to rising costs for components such as chips and batteries, which may mean margins remain under pressure.</p>\n<p>As demand falls and prices rise at home, China’s carmakers will become even more reliant on foreign sales, which are advancing in leaps and bounds. In April they were up 80% year on year. Setting up foreign distribution networks is costly and time-consuming. But as pressure on the industry continues to intensify, foreign sales, which tend to have higher margins, will make all the difference. China’s EV-makers are eager to hoover them up.<span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>To track the trends shaping commerce, industry and technology, sign up to “<a href=\"https://www.economist.com/newsletters/the-bottom-line\">The Bottom Line</a>”, our weekly subscriber-only newsletter on global business.</p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//business/2026/06/24/strange-new-ev-makers-keep-appearing-in-china\">https://www.economist.com//business/2026/06/24/strange-new-ev-makers-keep-appearing-in-china</a> </p>"
