        "id": "art_2026-06-27_064",
        "section": "Science & technology",
        "category": "analysis",
        "title": "Do high-tech “add-ons” increase the chance that IVF will work?",
        "title_zh": "高科技「附加项目」能否提高IVF成功率?",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-06-27/64",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\n《柳叶刀-妇产科与女性健康》于2026年6月23日发表的大型综述显示,绝大多数IVF「附加项目」缺乏可靠证据支持,且相关随机对照试验中近半数存在数据造假嫌疑。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n- **IVF失败率高催生附加服务**:约60%的IVF尝试以失败告终,生育诊所借此推出大量所谓能提高成功率的附加检测与项目,形成商业化乱象。\n- **大型综述规模与方法**:2026年6月23日发表于《柳叶刀-妇产科与女性健康》的综述审查了157项关于IVF附加项目的随机对照试验,并采用2023年由生育研究人员(含本综述部分作者)开发的清单进行数据完整性筛查,重点排查试验时间线不合理、受试者数据异常、文件记录缺失等可疑迹象。\n- **近半试验被剔除**:在157项试验中,近半数未通过审查,反映出医学研究中造假问题日益严重;剩余85项试验覆盖十种常用附加项目。\n- **仅三项「勉强有效」**:仅有子宫内膜搔刮(Endometrial scratching)、EmbryoGlue(将胚胎浸入天然存在于生殖道的透明质酸溶液)以及生理性卵胞浆内单精子注射(PICSI,旨在筛选高质量精子)这三项显示出益处,但证据强度并不高。\n- **三项无效,四项证据不足**:皮质类固醇(抗炎药物)、胚胎染色体异常基因检测、子宫内膜活检评估基因表达等三项有限数据显示无效;针灸、卵或大豆来源脂肪的静脉注射(试图抑制对胚胎的免疫反应)、向子宫或卵巢注射富血小板血浆(富含组织修复蛋白)等四项数据过少,无法做出判断。\n- **试验样本量普遍偏小**:所有纳入研究的中位样本量仅约160名患者,严重限制了对细微效应的检测能力;综述作者亦无法排除某些干预可能对特定亚群患者有效。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n原文未呈现明显的双方辩论,但隐含诊所商业利益推广附加项目与科学证据不支持其有效性之间的张力;此外,大量试验存在数据操纵嫌疑,使得现有证据基础本身就不够可靠。\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n综述作者明确呼吁「需要更多更好的研究」,并强调「需要眼光敏锐的期刊编辑在发表前剔除可疑研究」;预计未来该领域将加强试验注册与数据审查,并针对特定患者亚群开展更大规模的随机对照试验,以厘清各附加项目的真实价值。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">Science &amp; technology</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | Misconceptions</span></p>\n<h1>Do high-tech “add-ons” increase the chance that IVF will work?</h1>\n<h3>A big new review suggests most such procedures don’t help</h3>\n<h3>June 25th 2026</h3>\n<p>TRYING TO conceive through in vitro fertilisation (IVF) leads to disappointment more often than not. About 60% of IVF attempts fail. Fertility clinics offer a long list of tests and procedures purported to boost their customers’ chances. But a review of the evidence, published on June 23rd in the Lancet Obstetrics, Gynaecology &amp; Women’s Health, found no convincing evidence that most of these “IVF add-ons” are helpful. Worryingly, lots of the published evidence was dubious.</p>\n<p>The review examined 157 randomised trials of various IVF add-ons. The researchers ran each through a checklist designed to spot signs that the data may have been manipulated. That list was developed in 2023 by fertility researchers (including some of the review’s authors) who had noticed a growing number of <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/science-and-technology/2023/02/22/there-is-a-worrying-amount-of-fraud-in-medical-research\">fraudulent studies</a>. They looked for things such as implausible study timelines, strange participant data or holes in a trial’s paper trail.</p>\n<p>All told, nearly half of the trials did not pass muster. The remaining 85 covered ten commonly used add-ons. Of those, only three procedures showed evidence of abenefit, although the evidence was not particularly strong. The three procedures in question were endometrial scratching (which involves deliberately disturbing the lining of the uterus), EmbryoGlue (in which an embryo is dipped in a solution of hyaluronic acid, which is naturally found in the reproductive tract), and physiological intracytoplasmic sperm injection or PICSI (which tries to select high-quality individual sperm cells).</p>\n<p>The data on three other IVF add-ons, though also limited, suggested they had no effect on the chances of a successful pregnancy. These three were corticosteroids (a class of anti-inflammatory drugs), genetic testing of the embryo for abnormal chromosomes and biopsy of the uterine lining to assess genetic expression.</p>\n<p>Data for the remaining four procedures were too scant to make a judgment either way. These were acupuncture, intravenous infusion of fats derived from eggs or soyabeans (in the hope this might calm an immune reaction to the embryo), and injections of platelet-rich plasma into either the uterus or the ovaries (platelets being rich in tissue-rejuvenating proteins).</p>\n<p>The trials were not just few in number but mostly small in scale too. The median trial had only about 160 patients, which would limit its ability to detect small or subtle effects. The reviewers could not rule out the idea that some interventions might work for a subset of patients. But being able to say who, if anyone, might benefit from any of them would require more and better research—as well as eagle-eyed journal editors weeding out the fishy sort before it is published. <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>Curious about the world? To enjoy our mind-expanding science coverage, sign up to <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/newsletters/simply-science\">Simply Science</a>, our weekly subscriber-only newsletter.</p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//science-and-technology/2026/06/24/do-high-tech-add-ons-increase-the-chance-that-ivf-will-work\">https://www.economist.com//science-and-technology/2026/06/24/do-high-tech-add-ons-increase-the-chance-that-ivf-will-work</a> </p>"
