        "id": "art_2026-07-04_069",
        "section": "Culture",
        "category": "analysis",
        "title": "Heinz tomato ketchup and the sweet taste of market dominance",
        "title_zh": "亨氏番茄酱:统治世界餐桌150年的甜蜜霸主",
        "url": "https://www.economist.com/node/2026-07-04/69",
        "summary_md": "### 🌟 一句话核心主旨\n亨氏番茄酱自1876年问世以来畅销150年,凭借口感、配方创新与持续营销,成为全球最具支配地位的调味品品牌之一,堪称怀旧与商业策略完美结合的产物。\n\n### 🔍 核心观点与论据拆解\n- **销量与规模惊人**:亨氏每年售出逾6.5亿瓶番茄酱,平均每分钟有1,200多瓶被买走;其工厂每天处理的番茄量足以填满一个奥运标准泳池,普及程度堪称全球现象。\n- **配方与文化演进**:番茄酱源于亚洲发酵鱼酱「ke-tsiap」,17世纪末英国与荷兰商人引入西方却无法复制,早期西方版本用蘑菇、李子或核桃制作,「catsup」是19世纪的另一种拼法。\n- **19世纪美国化与早期痛点**:19世纪初美国人开始把番茄酱搭配鸡蛋、咸牛肉末和猪肝食用,但早期版本稀薄易坏,制造商用染色瓶遮瑕,并以苯甲酸钠和煤焦油染料防腐。\n- **亨氏的关键创新**:Henry J. Heinz(德国移民后裔)用熟透番茄提升风味与色泽,以醋抑制微生物,坚持不加防腐剂(广告语为「NOT drugged」),并率先采用透明玻璃瓶传递高品质信号。\n- **口感、怀旧与营销铁三角**:《The Condiment Book》作者Claire Dinhut称其完美平衡甜、鲜、酸,可搭配薯条鸡块等童年食物,也是美国7月4日国庆标配;YouGov民调显示100%英国人和97%美国人都知道亨氏,其「It has to be Heinz」的广告语已成为自我应验的预言。\n\n### 🤨 争议与潜在挑战\n原文未涉及明显争议\n\n### 🔮 未来趋势预判\n面对更便宜、手工与高端番茄酱的激烈竞争,以及消费者对减糖、清洁配方的日益关注,亨氏若想延续150年的统治地位,必须在怀旧营销与配方创新之间找到新平衡,巩固其「默认番茄酱」的心智占位。",
        "content_raw": "<p><span class=\"te_section_title\">Culture</span><span class=\"te_fly_span\"> | World in a dish</span></p>\n<h1>Heinz tomato ketchup and the sweet taste of market dominance</h1>\n<h3>The condiment that conquered the world was created 150 years ago</h3>\n<h3>July 2nd 2026</h3>\n<p>EATING HABITS have changed a lot in the past 150 years. Offal and jellied <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/christmas-specials/2019/12/21/the-mysterious-life-and-times-of-eels\">eels</a> rarely make it onto Britons’ and Americans’ plates any more. But one food product has remained a staple since it first hit shelves in 1876: Heinz tomato ketchup.</p>\n<p>Heinz says it sells over 650m bottles of the red stuff every year (meaning that more than 1,200 bottles land in shopping baskets every minute). Its factories process enough tomatoes each day to fill an Olympic swimming pool. The ubiquity of its ketchup is partly a matter of taste and partly a triumph of marketing.</p>\n<p>Versions of the condiment long predated Henry J. Heinz, a son of German immigrants to America. Ketchup is probably derived from ke-tsiap, a sauce made in Asia from fermented fish. It is thought British and Dutch traders encountered the salty, savoury sauce in the late 17th century and tried in vain to recreate it at home. Recipes often used <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/culture/2026/01/06/spore-of-the-moment-mushrooms-are-the-latest-wellness-food-trend\">mushrooms</a>, but others made ketchup with plums or walnuts. (In the 1800s, the spelling “catsup” was also used.)</p>\n<p>It was in the early 19th century that Americans developed a taste for tomato ketchup, plopped on eggs and corned beef hash or liver. Early versions of the sauce, however, were watery and spoiled easily. Manufacturers would package their sauces in coloured bottles to hide evidence of bacteria or mould; they would also use preservatives such as sodium benzoate and dyes made from coal tar. Many consumers, even then, wanted to eat clean.</p>\n<p>So Heinz developed a ketchup that would not go off quickly, but was free from preservatives (or, as an advert pithily put it, “NOT drugged”). He used ripe <a href=\"https://www.economist.com/culture/2025/07/31/the-humble-tomato-salad-holds-lessons-for-how-to-eat-well\">tomatoes</a> for a better flavour and colour, and vinegar to inhibit microbes. Crucially, Heinz sold his product in glass bottles, thereby signalling its higher quality.</p>\n<p>“The beauty of Heinz is that it’s not trying to be complicated,” says Claire Dinhut, author of “The Condiment Book”: “It’s the perfect balance of sweet and umami and tangy.” That sweetness pairs well with salty foods; the tanginess cuts through greasy dishes. Cookbooks aver that it is so versatile it can be used in curries, fish dishes and breads. But for many Heinz ketchup is associated with the comfort food of childhood—chicken nuggets and chips—and (for Americans) July 4th celebrations.</p>\n<p>Nostalgia helps explain Heinz’s staying power. Marketing has entrenched its position. Heinz is among the best-known brands globally: according to YouGov, a pollster, 100% of Britons and 97% of Americans know it. By advertising itself as the default ketchup, Heinz has turned that message into a self-fulfilling prophecy. Even today, when there are umpteen other ketchups on the market—including cheaper and artisan varieties—many shoppers still believe that “It has to be Heinz.” <span class=\"span_ufinish\">■</span></p>\n<p>This article was downloaded by <a class=\"producer_link\" href=\"https://z-lib.io\">zlibrary</a> from <a class=\"origin_link\" href=\"https://www.economist.com//culture/2026/07/02/heinz-tomato-ketchup-and-the-sweet-taste-of-market-dominance\">https://www.economist.com//culture/2026/07/02/heinz-tomato-ketchup-and-the-sweet-taste-of-market-dominance</a> </p>"
